<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-03">
  <title>Greek Mathematics (3.1-5.2)</title>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-Euclid">
  <title>Euclid and The Elements</title>
  


<p>
  Western mathematics is heavily influenced by Ancient Greek mathematics. In fact the word mathematics comes from a Greek word mathema, meaning <q>that which is learned</q>
</p>

<p>
  Unlike Babylon and Egypt, which were empires, the Ancient Greek civilization was a collection of city states in the Eastern Mediterranean that shared a common language and culture. When we talk about Greek Mathematics we mean mathematicians who were part of this shared culture and not just mathematicians living in the borders of modern day Greece. As an example, an important center of Greek mathematics was Alexandria in Egypt, which was home to the famous Library of Alexandria and its associated school, called the Musaeum, which brought together scholars throughout the world.
</p>

<p>
  Famous mathematicians who studied at the Musaeum were Archimedes, Eratosthenes, Hero, and Euclid.
</p>

<p>
  Despite being one of the most influential mathematicians of all time, very little is known about Euclid. This has led some historians to hypothesize that the works of Euclid were written by a team of mathematicians who took the name Euclid from Euclid of Megara, a philosopher who lived 100 years earlier. 
</p>

<p>
  Around 300 B.C. Euclid wrote The Elements, a mathematical textbook that covered geometry, number theory, and algebra.
</p>

<p>
  Euclid most likely didn't come up with a single proposition in The Elements. Instead he collected theorems, postulates, and demonstrations of other mathematicians.
</p>

<p>
  The Elements is one of the most influential mathematics textbooks ever written. For many years it was the standard textbook for anyone studying geometry. Over 1,000 editions of The Elements have been published, the most of any book except for The Bible.
</p>

<p>
  Ancient Greek mathematics was deductive, meaning that propositions are proved by showing that they are logical consequences of previously accepted statements. Suppose that we show that proposition A follows by assuming proposition B. Then we need to prove B. If we prove B using proposition A, then we fall into the trap of circular reasoning, so we must prove B using another proposition, C. But then we need to prove C without using A or B. Since this chain of reasoning can't be carried back forever, we must assume at the start some truths that we accept as obvious. These are known as axioms or postulates. You might think of these as the rules of the game of mathematics, and everything else comes from following the rules.
</p>

<p>
  Euclid began The Elements by accepting 5 axioms and 5 postulates.
</p>

<p>
  The 5 axioms are
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Things that are equal to the same thing are also equal to one another.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        If equals be added to equals, the wholes are equal.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        If equals be subtracted from equals, the remainders are equal.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Things that coincide with one another are equal to one another.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        The whole is greater than the part.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</p>

<p>
  The 5 postulates are
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        It is possible to draw a straight line from any point to any other point.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        It is possible to produce a finite straight line indefinitely in that straight line.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        It is possible to describe a circle with any point as center and with a radius equal to any straight line drawn from the center.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        All right angles are equal to one another.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        If a straight line intersects two straight lines so as to make the interior angles on one side of it together less than two right angles, these straight lines will intersect, if indefinitely produced, on the side on which are the angles which are together less than two right angles.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</p>

<p>
  Postulate 5 is also known as the parallel postulate because it involves parallel lines. Because it is much wordier than the other 4 postulates, and because it is not self-evident, for thousands of years many attempts were made to prove the it using the other axioms and postulates. There is even evidence that Euclid himself only included it as a postulate when he realized that he could neither prove it nor proceed without it. We will return to this problem near the end of the course when we discuss non-Euclidean geometry. There we will see how this difficulty was resolved.
</p>

<p>
  To get a feel for how Euclid approached geometry, let us consider Proposition 1 from Book 1 of the Elements.
</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>
    <em>To construct an equilateral triangle on a given finite straight line</em>
  </p>

  <p>
    Let <m>AB</m> be the given finite straight line.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is required to construct an equilateral triangle on the straight line <m>AB</m>
  </p>

  <p>
    Describe the circle <m>BCD</m> with center <m>A</m> and radius <m>AB</m>. Again describe the circle <m>ACE</m> with center <m>B</m> and radius <m>BA</m>. Join the straight lines <m>CA</m> and <m>CB</m> from the point <m>C</m> at which the circles cut one another to the points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>
  </p>

  <p>
    Now, since the point <m>A</m> is the center of the circle <m>CDB</m>, therefore <m>AC</m> equals <m>AB</m>. Again, since the point <m>B</m> is the center of the circle <m>CAE</m>, therefore <m>BC</m> equals <m>BA</m>. 
  </p>

  <p>
    But <m>AC</m> was proved equal to <m>AB</m>, therefore each of the straight lines <m>AC</m> and <m>BC</m> equals <m>AB</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    And things which equal the same thing also equal one another, therefore <m>AC</m> also equals <m>BC</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Therefore the three straight lines <m>AC</m>, <m>AB</m>, and <m>BC</m> equal one another.
  </p>

  <p>
    Therefore the triangle <m>ABC</m> is equilateral and it has been constructed on the given finite straight line <m>AB</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Q.E.F.
  </p>


</blockquote>

<p>
  Q.E.F. at the end of Proposition 1 stands for <term>Quod Erat Faciendum</term>, Latin for <q>which had to be done</q>. Euclid used this expression as the close of constructions in the Elements. The similar Q.E.D. which stands for <term>Quod Erat Demonstrandum</term>, Latin for <q>what was to be shown</q> is used at the end of theorems.
</p>

<p>
  Note that Euclid does not only give the procedure for constructing the equilateral triangle, but he also proves that the resulting construction is an equilateral triangle. In contrast, Egyptian and Babylonian mathematics did not emphasize proofs and did not include them.
</p>

<p>
  Despite the thoroughness of Euclid's construction and proof, several objections have been raised concerning Proposition 1. As it turns out there are several gaps in the proof where Euclid assumes something to be true without sufficient justification.
</p>

<p>
  One critique of Euclid's proof is the question of why the point <m>C</m> exists. The point <m>C</m> is mentioned as the point where the circles intersect, but no justification is given for why the circles have to intersect or why they can only intersect at a single point. Some postulate is needed such as <q>If the sum of the radii of two circles is greater than the line joining their centers then the two circles intersect.</q> 
</p>

<p>
  Another criticism was given by Zeno of Sidon, an Epicurean philosopher in the early first century B.C. who sought to show that deductions from the fundamental principals of geometry cannot be proved. He questioned why <m>ABC</m> contains an equilateral triangle and argued that was not shown that the sides do not meet before they reach the vertices. If <m>AB</m> and <m>BC</m> meet at <m>E</m> before they reach <m>C</m> then the straight lines <m>AEC</m> and <m>BEC</m> have a common segment <m>EC</m>. They would contain a triangle <m>ABE</m> which is not equilateral but isosceles. 
</p>

<p>
  Many of the problems in the Elements concern the construction of various geometric shapes using a straightedge and a compass. The straightedge and compass are generalizations of real world rulers and compasses.
</p>

<p>
  The straightedge is infinitely long, but has no markings on it, unlike ordinary rulers. It can only be used to draw a line segment between 2 points or to extend an existing line segment.
</p>

<p>
  The compass can be opened infinitely wide, but has no markings on it. Circles can be drawn starting from 2 different points: the center, and a point on the circle.
</p>

<p>
  Each construction must be exact; looking at the construction and guessing at its accuracy or using a ruler to measure it and getting close doesn't count as a solution.
</p>

<p>
  Each construction must terminate. It must have a finite number of steps and not be the limit of ever closer approximations.
</p>

<p>
  As an example, the following steps show how to find the midpoint of a line segment.
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Open the compass a distance that is between half the length of the line segment and the entire line segment.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Draw a circle centered at one endpoint; then draw a second circle centered at the other endpoint.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        These circles intersect at 2 points. Draw a line between the 2 points. The place where the line intersects the line segment is the midpoint of the line segment.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</p>

<p>
  Many geometric figures are constructible using only a straightedge and compass. These include finding a perpendicular bisector to a line segment, finding the midpoint of a line segment, bisecting an angle, constructing a line through a point tangent to a circle, and drawing a line through a given point parallel to a given line.
</p>

<p>
  These constructions were known to the Ancient Greeks and many appear in Euclid's Elements. For example, Proposition 9 gives the construction of a bisector of a given angle.
</p>

<p>
  The elements consists of thirteen books. Contrary to popular belief the Elements discusses more than just geometry. Books I-VI discuss plane geometry, books VII-X discuss number theory, and books XI - XIII discuss solid geometry. 
</p>

<p>
  Book I begins with a list of axioms, postulates, and definitions. It also includes 48 propositions including a proof that the base angles of an isosceles triangle are equal (Proposition 5) and the Pythagorean Theorem (Proposition 48)
</p>

<p>
  Book II focuses on area and quadrature, meaning the construction of a square of equal area to a given figure. Proposition 11 features a division of a line segment into a proportion called the golden ratio.
</p>

<p>
  Book III deals with the properties of circles. 
</p>

<p>
  Book IV deals with the problem of inscribing a polygon within a circle and circumscribing a polygon about a circle.
</p>

<p>
  Book V deals with ratios and proportions.
</p>

<p>
  Book VI applies the theory of ratios from Book V and applies it to plane geometry. Proposition 25 constructs from 2 given polygons, a third polygon that is similar to the first and has the same area as the second. The Greek historian Plutarch called it <q>more subtle and more scientific</q> than the Pythagorean theorem.
</p>

<p>
  Book VII deals with number theory and includes propositions for finding the greatest common divisor and least common multiple.
</p>

<p>
  Book VIII deals with geometric sequences, square numbers, and cube numbers.
</p>

<p>
  Book IX includes a proof that there are infinitely many prime numbers (Proposition 20), the formula for the sum of a finite geometric series (Proposition 35) and a construction using this sum for even perfect numbers. A number is perfect if it equals the sum of its proper divisors. For example the proper divisors of <m>6</m> are <m>1,2</m> and <m>3</m> and <m>1+2+3=6</m> so <m>6</m> is a perfect number. In the 18th century Leonhard Euler proved that this construction generates all even perfect numbers. 
</p>

<theorem xml:id="thm-prop-36">
  <title>Book IX Proposition 36</title>
  
  
  <statement>
    <p>
      An even number is perfect if it has the form <m>2^{p-1}(2^p-1)</m> where <m>2^p-1</m> is a prime number.
    </p>
  </statement>
</theorem>

<p>
  Example: If <m>p=2</m> then <m>2^p-1 = 3</m> which is prime and <m>2^{p-1} = 2</m>. Hence <m>6</m> is a perfect number.
</p>

<proof>
  <p>
    Let <m>\sigma(p)</m> denote the sum of the divisors of <m>p</m> including <m>p</m> itself. Thus <m>p</m> is a perfect number if <m>\sigma(p) = 2p</m>. Note that if <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> have no divisors in common then <m>\sigma(ab) = \sigma(a)\cdot \sigma(b)</m>. For example, <m>\sigma(36) = 1+2+3+4+6+9+12+18+36 = 91</m>, <m>\sigma(9) = 1+3+9 = 13</m> and <m>\sigma(4) = 1+2+4=7</m>
  </p>

  <p>
    By the multiplicative property of <m>\sigma</m>, when <m>2^p-1</m> is prime,
    <md>
      \sigma(2^{p-1}(2^p-1)) = \sigma(2^{p-1}) \sigma(2^p-1)
    </md>
    
  </p>

  <p>
    The divisors of <m>2^{p-1}</m> are <m>1,2,4,8, \ldots 2^{p-1}</m> whose sum is a geometric series whose sum is <m>2^p-1</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Since <m>2^p-1</m> is prime, its divisors are <m>1</m> and <m>2^p-1</m> so the sum of its divisors is <m>2^p</m>
  </p>

  <p>
    Thus
    <md>
      <mrow>  \sigma(2^{p-1}(2^p-1)) \amp = \sigma(2^{p-1}) \sigma(2^p-1) </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =(2^p-1)(2^p)</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =2(2^{p-1})(2^p-1)</mrow>
    </md>
    and thus <m>2^{p-1}(2^p-1)</m> is perfect.
  </p>

</proof>

<p>
  Book X deals with irrational numbers. Proposition 9 proves that square roots of non-square integers such as <m>\sqrt{2}</m> are irrational.
</p>

<p>
  Book XI discusses parallelpipeds, solids with three pairs of parallel faces.
</p>

<p>
  Book XII discusses the volumes of cones, pyramids, and cylinders using the method of exhaustion. It includes a proof that the volume of a cone is one third the volume of the corresponding cylinder.
</p>

<p>
  Book XIII discusses the five regular polyhedron: the tetrahedron, cube, octahedron, dodecahedron, and icosahedron. A regular polyhedron is a solid whose faces are regular polygons that are equal in shape and size and the same number of faces meet at each vertex. It concludes by showing that these are the only regular polyhedron.
</p>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-Three-Famous-Problems">
  <title>Three Famous Problems</title>


  <p>
    Three famous construction problems posed by the Greeks went unsolved until modern times. The problems are
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Doubling the cube 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Trisecting the angle
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Squaring the circle
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>

  <p>
    Though unsolved by the Greeks, the search for solutions to these problems heavily influenced Greek geometry and led to many new discoveries.
  </p>

  <p>
    The first of these problems is the problem of doubling the cube. Legend has it that citizens of Delos were told by the Oracle that in order to stop a plague sent by Apollo, they needed to double the size of Apollo's altar, which was a perfect cube. Supposedly when they asked Plato about it, he replied that the Oracle meant, not that the god wanted an altar of double the size, but that he wished in setting them the task to shame the Greeks for their neglect of mathematics and their contempt of geometry.  
  </p>

  <p>
    The problem of doubling the cube is as follows: Given the edge of a cube, construct the edge of a second cube whose volume is double that of the first.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before we delve into the solution of this problem, let us first consider a construction that the Greeks knew how to perform: doubling the square.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Dialogue <term>Meno</term> written by Plato is an account of a conversation between the philosopher Socrates and Meno concerning the nature of virtue. In it, Socrates argues that knowledge is not learned but rather is recollected. At one point, to illustrate his ideas, he interrogates one of Meno's slaves who is ignorant of geometry. Socrates draws a square with side lengths 2 feet on the ground and asks the slave how much the length of the side must be in order to double the length of the original square. At first the slave guesses that the original length must be doubled (4ft) but Socrates shows that this leads to a square that is four times as large. Next the slave guesses three feet, but Socrates shows that this is still too large and the slave admits that he does not know the answer. 
  </p>

  <p>
    Socrates draws three more squares to the original square to form a square that is four times as large. Then he draws four diagonal lines through each of the four squares and by only asking questions leads the slave to see that the square made by these diagonals has an area of eight square feet, twice the area of the original. He claims that the slave made the discovery without ever being taught anything about geometry and thus has recollected the knowledge that he had before he was born. 
  </p>

  <p>
    The example from <term>Meno</term> shows that the Greeks knew how to construct a square with double the area of a given square.
  </p>

  <p>
    Using algebra we can calculate the length of the second square. Suppose the first square has length <m>1</m> and the second square has length <m>x</m>. If the second square has double the area of the first square than <m>x^2 = 2</m>. Thus <m>x = \sqrt{2}</m>, which is why constructing the sides of the second square from the diagonal of the first square produces a square with double the area.
  </p>

  <p>
    Now let's use algebra to find the edge length of a cube with double the volume. Suppose a cube has edge length <m>1</m> so that its volume is <m>1 \cdot 1 \cdot 1 = 1</m> and that a second cube has double the volume of the first cube. We can calculate the length of the second edge using algebra. Let <m>x</m> be the length of the second edge. Then <m>x^3 = 2</m>, so <m>x = \sqrt[3]{2}</m>. 
  </p>

  <p>
    The problem is that it is impossible to construct an edge with measure <m>\sqrt[3]{2}</m> from an edge with measure <m>1</m> using only a straightedge and compass. This remarkable fact was proved in 1837 by Pierre Wantzel. There are ways to double the cube, but none involving only a straightedge and compass.
  </p>

  <p>
    The next famous unsolved problem of Greek mathematics is the problem of trisecting the angle. Similar to the first problem, we'll start by considering a construction that the Greeks knew how to do: bisecting an angle.
  </p>

  <p>
    The problem of bisecting the angle is as follows: Given an arbitrary angle, construct an angle with measure <m>1/2</m> of that of the original angle.
  </p>

  <p>
    Book I Proposition 9 of Euclid's elements gives the construction of an angle with half the measure as a given angle.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    <p>
      <em>To bisect a given rectilinear angle</em>
    </p>

    <p>
      Let the angle <m>BAC</m> be the given rectilinear angle. It is required to bisect it.
    </p>

    <p>
      Take an arbitrary point <m>D</m> on <m>AB</m>. Cut off <m>AE</m> from <m>AC</m> and join <m>DE</m>. Construct the equilateral triangle <m>DEF</m> on <m>DE</m> and join <m>AF</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      I say that the angle <m>BAC</m> is bisected by the straight line <m>AF</m>. 
    </p>

    <p>
      Since <m>AD = AE</m> and <m>AF</m> is common, therefore the two sides <m>AD</m> and <m>AF</m> equal the two sides <m>EA</m> and <m>AF</m> respectively.
    </p>

    <p>
      And the base <m>DF</m> equals the base <m>EF</m>, therefore the angle <m>DAF</m> equals the angle <m>EAF</m>. 
    </p>

    <p>
      Therefore the given rectilinear angle <m>BAC</m> is bisected by the straight line <m>AF</m>. Q.E.F.
    </p>

  </blockquote>

  <p>
    It is possible to trisect certain angles. The following procedure can be used to trisect a right angle.
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Draw a circle centered at the vertex of the angle.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Choose a point on a leg where the circle passes through. Draw a 2nd circle centered at this point with the same radius.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          The circles intersect at a 3rd point. Connect the 3rd point with the other 2 points to create an equilateral triangle. Since the angles of an equilateral triangle measure 60 degrees, The remaining part of the right angle measures 30 degrees. Thus the angle is trisected.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>

  <p>
    The <term>Book of Lemmas</term>, a work introduced by the Arabic scholar Thabit ibn-Qurra in the 9th century AD but attributed to Archimedes contains a construction of a trisection of an arbitrary angle; however, it makes use of a technique called <term>neusis</term> which is not allowed by Euclid's rules for constructions with straightedge and compass.
  </p>

  <p>
    In a <term>neusis</term> construction, the straightedge is marked at two points and used to fit a line between the points into a diagram.
  </p>

  <p>
    The following procedure uses neusis to trisect an angle.

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Suppose the angle <m>ABC</m> is to be trisected. Draw a circle <m>DEF</m> with center <m>B</m> and any radius.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Extend <m>CB</m> through <m>D</m> and beyond.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Fit in a line <m>GHE</m> passing through <m>E</m> and a point <m>G</m> on the line <m>CB</m> so that a segment equal to the radius <m>BD</m> of the circle starts at <m>G</m> and ends at a point <m>H</m> on the circle. To do this you have to move <m>G</m> around until <m>H</m> lands on the circle. Draw <m>BH</m>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>

  </p>

  <p>
    Using results from Euclid's Elements we can show that the angle <m>EGC</m> is one-third of angle <m>ABC</m>. 
  </p>

  <proof>
    <p>
      Since the lines <m>GH</m>, <m>HB</m> and <m>BE</m> are equal, the triangles <m>GHB</m> and <m>HBE</m> are isosceles. By Proposition 5 of Book I, isosceles triangles have equal base angles and thus angle <m>HGB</m> equals <m>HBG</m> and <m>BHE</m> equals <m>BEH</m>. 
    </p>

    <p>
      Book I Proposition 32 states that the exterior angle of a triangle equals the sum of the opposite interior angles. Thus the exterior angle <m>BHE</m> of triangle <m>GHB</m> equals the sum of the equal angles <m>HGB</m> and <m>HBG</m>. Thus <m>BHE</m> is double <m>HGB</m>. Also <m>BEH</m> equals <m>BHE</m> so it also is double <m>HGB</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Again by this proposition, the exterior angle <m>ABC</m> of triangle <m>BEG</m> equals the sum of the equal angles <m>HGB</m> and <m>BEH</m>. But <m>BEH</m> is double <m>HGB</m> and thus <m>ABC</m> is triple <m>HGB</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Therefore, angle <m>GHB</m> is one third of angle <m>ABC</m>.
    </p>

  </proof>

  <p>
    Although some angles can be trisected with only a straightedge and compass; others cannot, so it is not possible to trisect an arbitrary angle. This fact was also proven by Pierre Wantzel in 1837.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is known which angles can be trisected. For a positive integer N, an angle of measure <m>\dfrac{2\pi}{N}</m> radians is trisectable if and only if <m>N</m> is not divisible by 3. 
  </p>

  <p>
    Since 90 degrees is <m>\dfrac{2\pi}{4}</m> radians, a 90 degree angle is trisectable. However, a 60 degree angle is not trisectable, because 60 degrees is <m>\dfrac{2\pi}{6}</m> radians.
  </p>

  <p>
    The last Ancient Greek construction problem is squaring the circle: Given a circle, construct a square with the same area.
  </p>

  <p>
    The first Greek to consider this problem was Anaxogoras around 450 B.C. who considered the problem while imprisoned for claiming that the sun was not a god and that the moon reflects the sun's light.
  </p>

  <p>
    This problem goes back further than the Greeks. The Rhind Papyrus shows that the Egyptians knew that an approximate solution is to this problem is to remove 1/9 from the diameter of the circle and then make a square out of that.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Ancient Greeks and Ancient Egyptians were not the only ones interested in solving this problem. Mathematicians in China, India, and the Islamic world also attempted to square the circle.
  </p>

  <p>
    Suppose that the circle has radius measuring <m>1</m> unit. Then the area of the circle is <m>\pi \cdot 1^2 = \pi</m>. Thus the side length of the square with the same area must be <m>\sqrt{\pi}</m>. If such a length were constructible, then it would be possible to construct a length of <m>\pi</m>. 
  </p>

  <p>
    Thus to show that it's impossible to square the circle, we must show that <m>\pi</m> is not constructible. 
  </p>

  <p>
    The problem of squaring the circle was finally solved in 1880 when Ferndinand Von Lindemann proved that <m>\pi</m> is transcendental, meaning that it is not the root of a polynomial with integer coefficients. It was known that transcendental numbers are not constructible.
  </p>

  <p>
    The popularity of the problem of squaring the circle has led to many amateur mathematicians presenting false proofs asserting that the construction was possible, despite the fact that it is known to be impossible. Typically these proofs would work by first <q>proving</q> that <m>\pi</m> is a rational number.
  </p>

  <p>
    One example is a book by Carl Heisel in 1931, <em>Behold! The Grand Problem No Longer Unsolved: The Circle Squared Beyond Refutation</em>
  </p>

  <p>
    The title page is even longer: <em>Behold! The Grand Problem No Longer Unsolved: The Circle Squared Beyond Refutation. Mathematical and Geometrical Demonstrations by Carl Theodore Heisel: Disproving Numerous Theorems, Problems, Postulates, Corollaries, Axioms, and Propositions with Ratios, Laws, and Rules Hitherto Unknown in the Mathematical and Geometric Science Naturally Growing Out of the Extraordinary and Significant Discoveries of a Lacking Link by Carl Theodore Faber, in the Demonstration of the World Renowned Pythagorean Problem Utterly Disproving its Absolute Truth, Although Demonstrated as such for 24 Centuries; and by This Discovery Establishing the Fact of the Existence of Perfect Harmony Between Arithmetic and Geometry as a Law of Nature, and Calculating to Settle Forever the Famous Dispute Between the Two Great Philosophical Schools</em>
  </p>

  <p>
    In the book he shows that <m>\pi = 3 \frac{13}{81}</m>. He also claims that irrational numbers don't exist, the Pythagorean Theorem is only true in special cases, and all right triangles have integer ratios.
  </p>

  <p>
    His arguments rely on faulty and misleading pictures, and incorrect reasoning. For instance, his <q>proof</q> that <m>\pi = 3 \frac{13}{81}</m> works for other values for <m>\pi</m> as well.
  </p>
  
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-Archimedes">
  <title>Archimedes</title>

  <p>
    Archimedes (about 287-212 B.C.) is considered by many to be the ancient world's greatest genius. Despite this, not much is known of his life. He was born in the city of Syracuse, a Greek colony on the island of Syracuse, about a generation after Euclid and most likely studied in Alexandria, which was the seat of Greek mathematics and where he would have encountered other leading mathematicians of the time. However, he spent most of his life in Syracuse and died there when the city was sacked by the Romans during the Second Punic War. Archimedes contributed to the defense of the city and is reported to have used created a weapon by using mirrors to reflect the sun's light to set enemy ships on fire.
  </p>

  <p>
    Archimedes is remembered for his inventions such as the screw pump and the compound pulley, but his mathematical achievements are just as impressive if not moreso.
  </p>

  <p>
    On of Archimedes' most important works is <em>The Measurement of a Circle</em> despite its short length. (It only contains three propositions.)
  </p>

  <p>
    Proposition I states that the area of a circle with circumference <m>C</m> and radius <m>r</m> is equal in area to a right triangle whose two legs measure <m>C</m> and <m>r</m>. In other words the area of a circle with radius <m>r</m> is <m>A = \pi r^2</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Proposition III gives an estimate of <m>\pi</m> as being greater than <m>3 \frac{10}{71}</m> but less than <m>3 \frac{1}{7}</m>. This gives an approximation of <m>3.14</m> which was the most accurate at the time.
  </p>

  <p>
    To determine this estimate Archimedes made use of a technique called the <term>method of exhaustion</term> which can be viewed as a forerunner to integral calculus.
  </p>

  <p>
    The idea behind the method of exhaustion is to inscribe and circumscribe a circle with two similar polygons. Then the area of the circle must lie between the areas of the two polygons. By increasing the number of angles in the polygons, the areas of the polygons get closer to the area of the circle and the approximation becomes more exact.
  </p>

  <p>
    Archimedes began by inscribing and circumscribing the circle with hexagons. The area of the hexagons can be found by dividing it into triangles and adding up the areas of the triangles. 
  </p>

  <p>
    Next he bisected each angle in both hexagons to create 12-sided polygons that inscribed and circumscribed the circle. He further repeated this process to obtain polygons with 24, 48, and 96 sides. It was by calculating the areas of the 96-sided polygons that he found the upper and lower bounds for <m>\pi</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Had he been able to continue this process to infinity, the areas of both polygons would have converged to the area of the circle, similar to how one uses an infinite number of rectangles to find the area underneath a curve in calculus. In this way the method of exhaustion can be viewed as a precursor to integral calculus. However, there is no evidence that Archimedes ever considered something like a limiting process to find the exact area; he only viewed the process as useful for finding approximations.
  </p>

  <p>
    The method of exhaustion was later reinvented by Chinese mathematicians who used it to determine more accurate estimates for <m>\pi</m>. The 3rd century A.D. mathematician Liu Hui used polygons with 384 sides to determine that
    <md>
      3.1410204 \leq \pi \leq 3.132904
    </md>
    and the 5th century A.D. mathematician Zu Chongzhi used polygons of 12,288 sides to estimate that
    <md>
      3.1415926 \leq \pi \leq 3.1415927
    </md>
  which is accurate to six decimal places. (Note that he did not actually draw such a polygon, but made use of an algorithm for determining the areas of such polygons developed by Liu Hui.)
  </p>


  <p>
    Another accomplishment of Archimedes is his work <em>The Sand-Reckoner</em> in which he set out to estimate the number of grains of sand in the universe. He explains his reasons for this in his address to King Gelon of Syracuse.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    <p>
      There are some, king Gelon, who think that the number of the sand is infinite in multitude; and I mean by the sand not only that which exists about Syracuse and the rest of Sicily but also that which is found in every region whether inhabited or uninhabited. Again there are some who, without regarding it as infinite, yet think that no number has been named which is great enough to exceed its magnitude. And it is clear that they who hold this view, if they imagined a mass made up of sand in other respects as large as the mass of the Earth, including in it all the seas and the hollows of the Earth filled up to a height equal to that of the highest of the mountains, would be many times further still from recognizing that any number could be expressed which exceeded the multitude of the sand so taken.
    </p>

    <p>
      But I will try to show you by means of geometrical proofs, which you will be able to follow, that, of the numbers named by me and given in the work which I sent to Zeuxippus, some exceed not only the number of the mass of sand equal in magnitude to the Earth filled up in the way described, but also that of the mass equal in magnitude to the universe.
    </p>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    As mentioned in his address to King Gelon, Archimedes had come up with a method for expressing very large numbers. Recall that Greek numerals did not allow for arbitrarily large numbers to be expressed like our modern place value system. In the Greek system putting <m>M</m> (for myriad) in front of a number multiplied it by <m>10,000</m>. Thus <m>M\beta = 10,000*2 = 20,000</m>. The largest number that can be written in this system is a myriad-myriad <m>MM = 10^8</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Archimedes called numbers up to <m>10^8</m> <term>first order numbers</term> and called <m>10^8</m> the <term>unit of the second order</term>. Multiplying this number by first order numbers gave <term>second order numbers</term> up to <m>10^8 \cdot 10^8 = 10^{16}</m> which he called the <term>unit of the third order</term>. Multiplication of number of lower order by the unit of the third order gave <term>third order numbers</term> and this process could be repeated indefinitely.
  </p>

  <p>
    Archimedes continued to name numbers in this way until he reached <m>(10^8)^{10^8}</m>. He called the orders that he had defined to be <term>orders of the first period</term> and called <m>(10^8)^{10^8}</m> the <term>unit of the second period</term>. He then constructed the <term>orders of the second period</term> by multiplying orders of the first period by the unit of the second period until he reached <m>(10^8)^{10^8} \cdot (10^8)^{10^8}</m> which is the <term>unit of the third order</term>. Archimedes continued this process until he reached orders of the myriad-myriath period. The largest number he named is the last number of this period which is
    <md>
      ((10^8)^{10^8})^{10^8} = 10^{8\cdot 10^{16}}.
    </md>
    In our notation this number is written as <m>1</m> followed by <m>80,000,000,000,000,000</m> zeros.
  </p>
  
  <p>
    Archimedes like most astronomers of the time believed that the universe was a sphere whose center was the Earth and whose radius was the distance from the earth to the sun. He assumed that the diameter of the Earth was greater than that of the moon but less than that of the sun and that the diameter of the sun was 30 times that of the moon. Thus
    <md>
      D_{sun} = 30 D_{moon} &lt; D_{earth}
    </md>
    
  </p>

  <p>
    In <em>The Sand Reckoner</em> Archimedes proved that the perimeter of a regular polygon of <m>1000</m> sides inscribed in a circle with the diameter of the universe was greater than <m>3</m> times the diameter of the universe but less than <m>1000</m> times the diameter of the sun. Hence
    <md>
      3D_{univ} &lt; 1000 D_{sun} &lt; 30,000 D_{earth}
    </md>
    
  </p>

  <p>
    The circumference of the earth was believed to be <m>300,000</m> stadia (<m>55,470</m>km) but to be sure he multiplied this by a factor of ten, thus assuming that
    <md>
      D_{earth} &lt; 1,000,000 \text{ stadia }.
    </md>
    
  </p>

  <p>
    From these assumptions, Archimedes concluded that the diameter of the universe was less than <m>10^{10}</m> stadia. Next, he supposed that a grain of sand had small but definite size. He estimated that <m>10,000</m> grains  of sand would fit in a poppy seed and that <m>40</m> poppy seeds lined in a row would exceed a finger-breath. Using <m>V = \frac{\pi}{6}D^3 &lt; D^3</m>, he calculated that a sphere of diameter one finger-breath would contain at most <m>64,000</m> poppy seeds or at most <m>640,000,000</m> grains of sand which is far less than one billion or <m>10^9</m>. Since one stadium is less than <m>1,000 = 10^4</m> finger-breaths the number of grains in a sphere of sand of diameter one stadium is less than <m>10^9</m>. Thus an upper bound for the number of grains of sand in a sphere with diameter one stadium is
    <md>
      10^9(10^4)^3 = 10^{21}.
    </md>
    
  </p>

  <p>
    Therefore a universe of diameter <m>10^10</m> stadia would contain less than
    <md>
      10^{21}(10^{10})^3 = 10^{51} \text{ grains of sand}
    </md>
    or in Archimedes' notation <term>one thousand units of the seventh order of numbers</term>
  </p>

  <p>
    Archimedes also applied his method to the <term>universe given by the hypothesis of Aristarchus</term>. Aristarchus' original works have been lost to history but we know about them from <em>The Sand Reckoner</em>. In another section addressed to King Gelon, Archimedes writes
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    <p>
      You are aware that <q>universe</q> is the name given by most astronomers to the sphere, the center of which is the center of the earth, while its radius is equal to the straight line between the center of the sun and the center of the Earth. This is the common account as you have heard from astronomers. But Aristarchus brought out a book consisting of certain hypotheses, wherein it appears, as a consequence of the assumptions made, that the universe is many times greater than the <q>universe</q> just mentioned. His hypotheses are that the fixed starts and the sun remain unmoved, that the earth revolves about the sun in the circumference of a circle, the sun lying in the middle of the orbit, and that the sphere of fixed stars, situated about the same center as the sun, is so great that the circle in which supposes the earth to revolve bears such a proportion to the distance of the fixed stars as the center of the sphere bears to its surface.
    </p>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    With these assumptions Archimedes calculated that the universe proposed by Aristarchus was no more than <m>10^{14}</m> stadia and that it would contain
    <md>
      10^{21}(10^{14})^3 = 10^{63} \text{ grains of sand}
    </md>
    so that even the number of grains of sand in Aristarchus' larger universe could be counted by Archimedes system.
  </p>

  <p>
    Another problem that illustrates Archimedes' fondness for large numbers is Archimedes' cattle problem. The problem was rediscovered in 1773 by Gotthold Ephraim Lessing who found it in a collection of Ancient Greek manuscripts. It consists of a poem of 44 lines containing a problem asking the reader to find the number of cattle in the herd of the sun god Helios. The heading states that it is <q>the problem which Archimedes discovered and sent in an epigram ... in a letter to Eratosthenes</q>
  </p>

  <p>
    The problem as translated states:
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    <p>
      If thou art diligent and wise, O stranger, compute the number of cattle of the Sun, who once upon a time grazed on the fields of the Thrinacian isle of Sicily, divided into four herds of different colours, one milk white, another a glossy black, a third yellow and the last dappled. In each herd were bulls, mighty in number according to these proportions: Understand, stranger, that the white bulls were equal to a half and a third of the black together with the whole of the yellow, while the black were equal to the fourth part of the dappled and a fifth, together with, once more, the whole of the yellow. Observe further that the remaining bulls, the dappled, were equal to a sixth part of the white and a seventh, together with all of the yellow. These were the proportions of the cows: The white were precisely equal to the third part and a fourth of the whole herd of the black; while the black were equal to the fourth part once more of the dappled and with it a fifth part, when all, including the bulls, went to pasture together. Now the dappled in four parts were equal in number to a fifth part and a sixth of the yellow herd. Finally the yellow were in number equal to a sixth part and a seventh of the white herd. If thou canst accurately tell, O stranger, the number of cattle of the Sun, giving separately the number of well-fed bulls and again the number of females according to each colour, thou wouldst not be called unskilled or ignorant of numbers, but not yet shalt thou be numbered among the wise.
    </p>

    <p>
      But come, understand also all these conditions regarding the cattle of the Sun. When the white bulls mingled their number with the black, they stood firm, equal in depth and breadth, and the plains of Thrinacia, stretching far in all ways, were filled with their multitude. Again, when the yellow and the dappled bulls were gathered into one herd they stood in such a manner that their number, beginning from one, grew slowly greater till it completed a triangular figure, there being no bulls of other colours in their midst nor none of them lacking. If thou art able, O stranger, to find out all these things and gather them together in your mind, giving all the relations, thou shalt depart crowned with glory and knowing that thou hast been adjudged perfect in this species of wisdom.
    </p>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    The first part of the problem can be solved by setting up a system of equations. Let <m>W,B,D,</m> and <m>Y</m> denote the white, black, dappled and yellow bulls and let <m>w,b,d,</m> and <m>y</m> denote the number of white, black, dappled, and yellow cows. Then the problem is to solve the system of equations
    <md>
      <mrow> W \amp = \frac{5}{6}B + Y</mrow>
      <mrow> B \amp = \frac{9}{20}D + Y</mrow>
      <mrow> D \amp = \frac{13}{42}W + Y</mrow>
      <mrow> w \amp = \frac{7}{12}(B+b) </mrow>
      <mrow> b \amp = \frac{9}{20}(D+d) </mrow>
      <mrow> d \amp = \frac{11}{30}(Y+y) </mrow>
      <mrow> y \amp = \frac{13}{42}(W+w)</mrow>
    </md>
    
  </p>

  <p>
    This is a system of seven equations and eight unknowns meaning that it is indeterminate and has infinitely many solutions. The smallest positive integer solution is
    <md>
      <mrow> B \amp = 7,460,514</mrow>
      <mrow> W \amp = 10,366,482</mrow>
      <mrow> D \amp = 7,358,060</mrow>
      <mrow> Y \amp = 4,149,387</mrow>
      <mrow> b \amp = 4,893,246</mrow>
      <mrow> w \amp = 7,206,360</mrow>
      <mrow> d \amp = 3,515,820</mrow>
      <mrow> y \amp = 5,439,213</mrow>
    </md>
    for a total of <m>50,389,082</m> cattle.
  </p>

  <p>
    The second part of this problem states that <m>W+B</m> is a perfect square and <m>Y+D</m> is a <term>triangular number</term>, a number that can be represented as lattice points arranged in a equilateral triangle. (The first few triangular numbers are <m>1, 3, 6, 10, 15</m>.) The solution to the second part of the problem was found by Carl Amthor in 1880 and is about <m>7.76 \times 10^{206,544}</m>. For comparison there are about <m>10^{80}</m> atoms in the observable universe.  
  </p>
  
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-Diophantus">
  <title>Diophantus</title>

  <p>
    We close this section by looking at a mathematician from the later Greek era of mathematics. Diophantus is unique in the history of Greek Mathematicians because unlike the other Greek mathematicians who approached mathematics from a geometrical viewpoint, Diophantus approached things algebraically. The French-Italian Mathematician Joseph-Louis Lagrange called Diophantus <q>the inventor of algebra</q>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Very little is known about Diophantus' life and even the details of his birth is obscure, but he probably lived in the 3rd century A.D. 
  </p>

  <p>
    Diophantus' fame rests on his book <em>Arithmetica</em> which is a collection of algebra problems. <em>Arithmetica</em> consisted of thirteen volumes, but only six have survived to modern times. The rest are lost to history. Like the Egyptian Rhind Papyrus, <em>Arithmetica</em> consists of a number of algebra problems and their solutions.
  </p>

  <p>
    One of the major contributions of <em>Arithmetica</em> is the notation that Diophantus used. The symbols that we use in mathematics such as <m>=, +, -, x^2</m> are all modern inventions. The plus sign may have been first used in the 14th century, the minus sign in the 15th century and the equals sign was created by Robert Recorde in 1557. Prior to this mathematical equations and formulas were written out in words. In <em>Arithmetica</em> Diophantus used syncopated algebra as a shorthand for expressing certain quantities and operations.
  </p>

  <p>
    Diophantus used <m>\zeta</m> to stand for the unknown variable, much like how we today would use <m>x</m>. However instead of <m>x^2</m> he wrote <m>\Delta^\tau</m> which were the first two letters in the Greek word for <q>power</q>. Similarly he used <m>K^\tau</m> to represent the cube of the unknown variable, from the Greek word for cube, <term>kubos</term>. For higher powers he used <m>\Delta^\tau \Delta</m> for <m>x^4</m>, <m>\Delta K^\tau</m> for <m>x^5</m> and <m>KK^\tau</m> for <m>x^6</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Note that he had no way to represent a second unknown in his notation, which hindered his work. As a result every problem in <em>Arithmetica</em> is solved by reducing it to a single variable equation, not matter how complicated, before expressing the single variable equation with his notation and solving it.
  </p>

  <p>
    Diophantus used the symbol <m>\iota\sigma</m> to represent equality between the sides of the equation, like our equal sign, and used the symbol 
  </p>
  
</subsection>

  </section>